@end menu

@node Networking Modes
@section Networking Modes

@opindex --net

@table @option
@item --net host
Share the host network stack (default).
@item --net none
Create an isolated network namespace with only a loopback interface.
@item --net container:@var{PID}
Join the network namespace of process @var{PID}.
@end table

@node Read-Only Rootfs
@section Read-Only Rootfs

@opindex --read-only
@cindex overlayfs

@option{--read-only} mounts the rootfs read-only via overlayfs.  Writes
go to a temporary upper layer discarded on exit; the on-disk rootfs is
never modified.  Falls back to read-write with a warning if overlayfs is
unavailable.

@example
./my-app --read-only
./my-app --read-only --tmpfs /tmp --tmpfs /var/run
@end example

@node Capabilities
@section Capabilities

@opindex --cap-drop
@opindex --cap-add
@cindex capabilities

@option{--cap-drop CAP} drops a capability from the bounding and
effective sets.  Pass @code{all} to drop every capability.
@option{--cap-add CAP} raises a capability as ambient so it survives
@code{exec(2)}.  Both are case-insensitive and the @code{CAP_} prefix is
optional.

@example
./my-app --cap-drop all
./my-app --cap-drop all --cap-add net_bind_service
./my-app --cap-drop net_raw --cap-drop sys_ptrace
@end example

@node Seccomp Filter
@section Seccomp Filter

@opindex --no-seccomp
@cindex seccomp

A default seccomp-BPF filter blocks syscalls with no legitimate use
inside a container:

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .65
@headitem Blocked syscall @tab Reason
@item @code{kexec_load}, @code{kexec_file_load} @tab Load a new kernel
@item @code{reboot} @tab Reboot the host
@item @code{syslog} @tab Kernel ring buffer access
@item @code{perf_event_open} @tab Used in kernel exploit chains
@item @code{bpf} @tab Load arbitrary BPF programs
@item @code{add_key}, @code{request_key}, @code{keyctl} @tab Kernel keyring manipulation
@item @code{userfaultfd} @tab Exploited in kernel escapes
@item @code{pivot_root} @tab Namespace escape vector
@item @code{ptrace} @tab Container escape
@item @code{process_vm_readv}, @code{process_vm_writev} @tab Cross-process memory access
@item @code{init_module}, @code{finit_module} @tab Kernel module loading
@end multitable

@code{PR_SET_NO_NEW_PRIVS} is always set.  To disable the filter:

@example
./my-app --no-seccomp
@end example

@node User Namespace
@section User Namespace

The loader always creates a user namespace (CLONE_NEWUSER) and maps the
host UID to UID@tie{}0 inside the container.  This makes the process
appear as root inside the container without granting real host
privileges.

@c ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@node Process Management
@chapter Process Management

@menu
* Init Process::
* Background Detach::
@end menu

@node Init Process
@section Init Process and Zombie Reaping

@opindex --init
@cindex zombie reaping
@cindex PID 1

@option{--init} runs a tiny zombie-reaping init as PID@tie{}1.  The
entrypoint is forked as a child; the parent loops reaping zombies.
@code{SIGTERM}, @code{SIGINT}, @code{SIGHUP}, @code{SIGUSR1}, and
@code{SIGUSR2} are forwarded to the child.  When the main child exits,
remaining zombies are drained and the exit status is returned.

@example
./my-app --init
./my-app --init --detach   # fully-managed background service
@end example

@node Background Detach
@section Running in Background

@opindex --detach

@option{--detach} (or @option{-d}) forks the container to the
background, prints the child PID to stdout, and exits.  The child calls
@code{setsid(2)} to detach from the terminal and redirects stdin from
@file{/dev/null}.

@example
PID=$(./redis --detach)
echo "Redis running as PID $PID"
sleep 1
kill "$PID"
@end example

@c ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@node Subcommands
@chapter Subcommands

Besides building, the @command{oci2bin} CLI provides these subcommands.

@table @code
@item oci2bin inspect BINARY [--json | --format TMPL]
Show embedded image metadata (name, arch, layers, entrypoint, cmd, env,
workdir, digest, build time); secret-shaped env values are redacted.
@item oci2bin explain BINARY [--json]
Inspect plus a host-capability check of what the binary needs to run.
@item oci2bin doctor [--json]
Probe the host for oci2bin's toolchain/kernel features and print a fix command
for each missing piece.
@item oci2bin list [--json]
List cached binaries.
@item oci2bin prune [--dry-run]
Remove stale cache entries.
@item oci2bin diff OLD NEW
Compare two binaries' filesystems (@code{+}/@code{-}/@code{M}).
@item oci2bin diff-fs OVERLAY_PATH
Classify an overlayfs upperdir (after @option{--overlay-persist}).
@item oci2bin sbom BINARY
Generate a Software Bill of Materials for the embedded image.
@item oci2bin reconstruct SRC [--output PATH]
Rebuild a polyglot from an image/tar carrying an embedded loader.
@item oci2bin push BINARY REF
Push the embedded image payload to an OCI registry.
@item oci2bin exec PID [--] CMD ...
Run a command inside a running container's namespaces (needs @command{nsenter}).
@item oci2bin ps / stop NAME / logs [-f] NAME
List, stop, and tail named detached containers.
@item oci2bin top [--once] [--interval SEC]
Live per-container resource stats.
@item oci2bin systemd BINARY [--user] [--restart POLICY]
Print a systemd unit for the binary.
@item oci2bin healthcheck BINARY [--pid PID]
Run the image's HEALTHCHECK once and report the result.
@item oci2bin freeze NAME [-- CMD] / thaw NAME
Quiesce SQLite-backed volumes for a consistent snapshot, and release it.
@item oci2bin checkpoint NAME / restore NAME
Dump and restore a running container with CRIU.
@item oci2bin sign --key KEY --in BIN [--rekor] [--attest A] / verify --key PUB --in BIN
Sign a binary (optionally publishing a Rekor entry / embedding an attestation)
and verify it.
@item oci2bin sign-file / verify-file
Sign or verify an arbitrary detached file.
@item oci2bin pod run [--net shared] [--ipc shared] BIN ...
Run several binaries sharing namespaces.
@item oci2bin up [-f stack.yaml] [-d] / down / stack @{up|down|logs|config@}
Bring a declarative stack of binaries up and down.
@item oci2bin run [BUILD_OPTS] IMAGE [-- ARGS]
Build to a temp file and run it in one step.
@item oci2bin from-chroot DIR [-o OUT] / build-dockerfile [-f FILE]
Build without Docker — from a chroot directory or a Dockerfile.
@item oci2bin mcp-serve [--allow-net]
Serve the Model Context Protocol interface for AI-agent integration.
@end table

@c ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
@node How It Works
@chapter How It Works

@cindex polyglot
@cindex ELF
@cindex tar archive

The output file is a polyglot: simultaneously a valid ELF64 executable
and a valid POSIX tar archive.

@example
Byte   0-3:   7f 45 4c 46   ELF magic  (kernel identifies as executable)
Byte 257-262: 75 73 74 61   ustar\0    (tar identifies as archive)
@end example

The 64-byte ELF header fits within the tar header's 100-byte filename
field.  When executed, the kernel processes the ELF; when passed to
@command{tar} or @command{docker load}, the tar structure is read.

@section File Layout

@example
[0-63]       ELF64 header  (embedded in the tar filename field)
[64-511]     Remaining tar header fields (ustar magic at byte 257)
[512-4095]   NUL padding   (page-aligns the loader for mmap)
[4096-~75K]  Loader binary (statically linked, gcc -static -O2 -s)
[~75K-end]   OCI image tar (manifest.json, config, layer tarballs)
@end example

@section Runtime Sequence

@enumerate
@item
Open @file{/proc/self/exe} and read the embedded OCI tar from the
patched offset.
@item
Extract image layers into a temporary rootfs under @file{/tmp} using
@command{tar --no-same-permissions --no-same-owner}.
@item
Patch @file{/etc/passwd} and @file{/etc/group} for single-UID namespace
compatibility (all UIDs/GIDs set to@tie{}0, except 65534).
@item
Enter a user namespace (@code{CLONE_NEWUSER}); map host UID to
container UID@tie{}0.
@item
Optionally join a shared network or IPC namespace via @code{setns(2)}.
@item
Enter mount, PID, and UTS namespaces.
@item
Apply volume bind mounts; optionally set up overlayfs.
@item
@code{chroot(2)} into the rootfs; mount @file{/proc}, @file{/tmp},
@file{/dev}.
@item
Apply seccomp filter, capabilities, UID drop.
@item
@code{exec(2)} the entrypoint.
@end enumerate

@section Security Properties

@itemize
@item
The process is unprivileged on the host; @code{CLONE_NEWUSER} does not
confer real root.
@item
Layer and config paths from the OCI manifest are validated against path
traversal.
@item
Volume container paths must be absolute and must not contain @code{..}.
@item
Tar extraction uses @option{--no-same-permissions --no-same-owner} to
prevent setuid bit restoration.
@item
Temporary directories are created with @code{mkdtemp} (mode
@code{0700}).
@end itemize

